TEXT(EV3(<<'EOT'));
$BR Hint: 
Think about the
\{htmlLink("http://www.math.utah.edu/online/1010/binom/",
"binomial formulas")\}
EOT

$ap1 = $a + 1;
$am1 = $a - 1;

SOLUTION(EV3(<<'EOT'));
$BR $BBOLD Solution:$EBOLD
By the binomial formula,
\[x^2+$a2 x+$as = (x+$a)^2.\]
Hence 



\[
\begin{array}{rcccccl}
\frac{1}{x^2+$a2 x+$as} + \frac{1}{x+$a} 
   &=& \frac{1}{(x+$a)(x+$a)} +\frac{1}{x+$a} 
   &=& \frac{1+x+$a}{(x+$a)(x+$a)} 
   &=& \frac{x+$ap1}{(x+$a)^2} \\ \\
\frac{1}{x^2+$a2 x+$as} - \frac{1}{x+$a} 
   &=& \frac{1}{(x+$a)(x+$a)} -\frac{1}{x+$a} 
   &=& \frac{1-(x+$a)}{(x+$a)(x+$a)} 
   &=& \frac{-x -$am1}{(x+$a)^2} \\ \\
\frac{1}{x^2+$a2 x+$as} \times \frac{1}{x+$a} 
   &=& \frac{1}{(x+$a)(x+$a)} \times \frac{1}{x+$a} 
   &=& \frac{1}{(x+$a)(x+$a)^2} 
   &=& \frac{1}{(x+$a)^3} \\ \\
\frac{1}{x^2+$a2 x+$as} \div \frac{1}{x+$a} 
   &=& \frac{1}{(x+$a)(x+$a)} \times \frac{x+$a}{1} 
   &&&=& \frac{1}{x+$a}
\end{array}
\]



